00:02:44,713 --> 00:02:46,734
And despite it being something that is so embedded

67
00:02:46,774 --> 00:02:47,955
into the fabric of society,

68
00:02:47,975 --> 00:02:49,435
I feel like we don't spend enough time

69
00:02:49,495 --> 00:02:50,796
talking about how it affects us,

70
00:02:51,256 --> 00:02:54,077
psychologically, emotionally, and how it shapes culture

71
00:02:54,197 --> 00:02:55,557
and the way that we talk about media.

72
00:02:56,278 --> 00:02:57,838
And we do this sometimes, and that's great,

73
00:02:58,218 --> 00:03:00,099
but a lot of the time, it looks like this.

74
00:03:01,469 --> 00:03:03,370
And what these are all really saying is just,

75
00:03:04,170 --> 00:03:05,571
we live in a society.

76
00:03:07,211 --> 00:03:09,552
And they aren't engaging with the real nuanced issues

77
00:03:09,592 --> 00:03:12,193
of the internet, of which there are a lot.

78
00:03:13,493 --> 00:03:14,314
So with all this in mind,

79
00:03:14,454 --> 00:03:15,714
today I wanna do a bit of a sequel

80
00:03:15,754 --> 00:03:17,175
to the talk that I gave here last year.

81
00:03:18,130 --> 00:03:20,212
It was about how understanding the historical origins

82
00:03:20,232 --> 00:03:22,354
of internet culture can help you make your game something

83
00:03:22,374 --> 00:03:24,376
that people will want to share online,

84
00:03:24,917 --> 00:03:26,798
and how we use the concept of metamodernism

85
00:03:26,838 --> 00:03:29,461
to make Dream Daddy a bit of a viral success.

86
00:03:30,261 --> 00:03:31,282
So, one second.

87
00:03:34,585 --> 00:03:35,746
Gotta get my gamer voice on.

88
00:03:36,507 --> 00:03:37,848
So I'm gonna do a quick high-level speed run

89
00:03:37,868 --> 00:03:38,769
of the stuff we talked about

90
00:03:38,849 --> 00:03:40,010
because it's relevant to this talk.

91
00:03:40,190 --> 00:03:40,611
Here we go.

92
00:03:40,951 --> 00:03:41,672
What's up, gamers?

93
00:03:42,642 --> 00:03:44,283
Modernism, sincere.

94
00:03:45,043 --> 00:03:47,764
Postmodernism is cynical, deconstruction

95
00:03:47,784 --> 00:03:48,744
of modernist ideals.

96
00:03:49,284 --> 00:03:51,745
Postmodernism is dead, long live metamodernism.

97
00:03:52,045 --> 00:03:52,485
What's that?

98
00:03:52,805 --> 00:03:54,286
The art period we're currently in.

99
00:03:55,066 --> 00:03:57,707
The entire idea is that it combines both modernism

100
00:03:57,887 --> 00:03:58,847
and postmodernism.

101
00:03:59,347 --> 00:04:02,328
So the guiding tenet is sincerity wrapped in cynicism,

102
00:04:02,768 --> 00:04:03,868
like a nice empanada.

103
00:04:06,106 --> 00:04:07,787
And just like how modernism was spurred on

104
00:04:08,047 --> 00:04:10,469
by the Industrial Revolution and post-modernism

105
00:04:10,709 --> 00:04:12,590
was spurred on by the proliferation of broadcast

106
00:04:12,630 --> 00:04:15,371
television, metamodernism's biggest influence

107
00:04:15,451 --> 00:04:16,592
is the advent of the internet.

108
00:04:17,232 --> 00:04:18,653
A lot of the most popular media today

109
00:04:18,753 --> 00:04:20,594
follows this guiding principle of sincerity

110
00:04:20,614 --> 00:04:22,556
wrapped in cynicism, like these things.

111
00:04:23,136 --> 00:04:27,078
Wow, wow, wow, wow, wow.

112
00:04:28,039 --> 00:04:28,239
But.

113
00:04:29,947 --> 00:04:33,268
What I didn't talk about last year is that sometimes,

114
00:04:33,488 --> 00:04:35,129
when your game gets really successful,

115
00:04:35,269 --> 00:04:37,870
when you kind of thought like four people max

116
00:04:37,950 --> 00:04:41,131
were gonna play it, it breaks your brain a little bit.

117
00:04:42,471 --> 00:04:43,231
So now that we're caught up,

118
00:04:43,791 --> 00:04:45,972
today I'm gonna talk about how I had a nervous breakdown

119
00:04:46,012 --> 00:04:47,432
after Dream Daddy became a success

120
00:04:47,753 --> 00:04:50,073
and how that breakdown forced me to reevaluate

121
00:04:50,133 --> 00:04:51,394
my relationship with the internet,

122
00:04:51,894 --> 00:04:54,295
my work, media criticism, and myself.

123
00:04:55,303 --> 00:04:59,486
So before we get into internet theory stuff, I want to also do a speedrun of what happened

124
00:04:59,526 --> 00:05:00,467
after Dream Daddy blew up.

125
00:05:03,529 --> 00:05:06,591
My friend Vern and I both love hot dads and are clinically depressed.

126
00:05:07,532 --> 00:05:11,114
Neither of us had ever made a game before, but we decided to do a game about hot dads

127
00:05:11,134 --> 00:05:12,255
who kiss each other anyway.

128
00:05:14,297 --> 00:05:17,179
We wanted to make it silly on the outside and sincere on the inside.

129
00:05:17,499 --> 00:05:18,159
Empanadas.

130
00:05:19,515 --> 00:05:22,998
We wrote the game together across the country from each other using Skype and Google Docs.

131
00:05:23,618 --> 00:05:27,040
We formed a ragtag group of cool game developers who are actually, some of them are sitting

132
00:05:27,060 --> 00:05:28,842
in the front row and they're great.

133
00:05:29,362 --> 00:05:31,403
And we worked out a publishing deal with our friends, the Game Grumps.

134
00:05:32,368 --> 00:05:34,969
Blah blah blah, year and a half of development goes by,

135
00:05:35,009 --> 00:05:36,130
nya nya nya, all right.

136
00:05:36,890 --> 00:05:40,292
So, as a bisexual woman, and Vernon being a straight dude

137
00:05:40,312 --> 00:05:42,813
but a good ally, we were fretting a lot

138
00:05:42,893 --> 00:05:44,594
about getting the queer representation right.

139
00:05:45,454 --> 00:05:47,455
So we were constantly showing the script to people,

140
00:05:47,515 --> 00:05:49,256
getting perspectives from other queer folks,

141
00:05:49,756 --> 00:05:51,837
researching, having sensitivity readers look at it,

142
00:05:52,017 --> 00:05:53,318
and a lot of the crew is queer,

143
00:05:53,438 --> 00:05:55,199
so we were feeling pretty good about it.

144
00:05:56,099 --> 00:05:59,520
Our mission statement from the beginning was to contribute something that was just a nice,

145
00:05:59,680 --> 00:06:04,082
funny, positive queer thing that was more focused on the romance angle than having to

146
00:06:04,262 --> 00:06:09,584
navigate being queer, because so often narratives about queer people are either really insensitive

147
00:06:09,844 --> 00:06:13,706
or are just hyper serious and angsty and all about struggling with your sexuality.

148
00:06:14,506 --> 00:06:18,788
And I do enough of that in real life. So we announced the game on Father's Day,

149
00:06:18,928 --> 00:06:20,528
only a few weeks before it was set to come out.

150
00:06:21,677 --> 00:06:26,179
The response was immediate and ridiculous and really unexpected for me.

151
00:06:27,039 --> 00:06:31,461
We spent all of announce day just trawling through socials reading everything, which

152
00:06:32,002 --> 00:06:34,143
is not a good idea at all.

153
00:06:35,603 --> 00:06:41,206
The issue was that we had still not completed or QA'd the game when we announced and we

154
00:06:41,246 --> 00:06:42,987
were kind of racing to the finish.

155
00:06:43,988 --> 00:06:46,129
But we did not anticipate the response.

156
00:06:46,229 --> 00:06:47,830
So now there was this added pressure

157
00:06:48,190 --> 00:06:51,612
of our 70,000 Twitter followers and lots of conversation

158
00:06:51,712 --> 00:06:53,113
and many, many articles about it.

159
00:06:53,653 --> 00:06:55,234
And there was already a lot of controversy.

160
00:06:56,494 --> 00:06:58,615
And not just from who you or even I

161
00:06:58,875 --> 00:07:00,536
would have expected either, i.e.,

162
00:07:00,896 --> 00:07:02,397
alt-right homophobe Gamergate types.

163
00:07:03,097 --> 00:07:03,858
And we got some of that.

164
00:07:04,358 --> 00:07:06,719
But it was overwhelmingly kind of calls

165
00:07:06,799 --> 00:07:08,059
coming from inside the house.

166
00:07:09,152 --> 00:07:11,394
The people that I had always wanted to be stoked about this game

167
00:07:11,995 --> 00:07:13,716
were the same ones who were really upset about it.

168
00:07:14,297 --> 00:07:16,299
And that was like a knife in the heart.

169
00:07:17,139 --> 00:07:19,381
Because my timeline was still all Dream Daddy stuff,

170
00:07:19,461 --> 00:07:21,743
but we also had people adding us nonstop

171
00:07:22,284 --> 00:07:23,104
with everything from,

172
00:07:23,385 --> 00:07:24,486
this is going to be homophobic

173
00:07:24,546 --> 00:07:27,008
and you should give money to actual queer creators.

174
00:07:28,570 --> 00:07:31,213
Instead of this game, to this is clearly just a cash grab,

175
00:07:31,293 --> 00:07:32,934
to Layton is not actually queer,

176
00:07:33,054 --> 00:07:35,797
to tell us exactly the sexualities of everyone in your team,

177
00:07:36,337 --> 00:07:38,239
to the one that I cried in corners about most,

178
00:07:38,780 --> 00:07:40,761
I'm queer and I want to be excited for this,

179
00:07:40,821 --> 00:07:42,383
but I know it will be bad and hurt me.

180
00:07:43,844 --> 00:07:45,486
And because the game hadn't come out yet,

181
00:07:45,666 --> 00:07:47,127
and honestly wasn't even finished,

182
00:07:47,988 --> 00:07:49,409
a lot of this was just speculation

183
00:07:49,589 --> 00:07:51,211
and we knew we couldn't address any of it

184
00:07:51,291 --> 00:07:53,052
because we wanted to let the game speak for itself.

185
00:07:53,888 --> 00:07:57,470
But the interim was torture and extremely overwhelming.

186
00:07:58,810 --> 00:08:00,911
And like, I totally get the reaction.

187
00:08:01,612 --> 00:08:03,313
As queer folks online, and honestly

188
00:08:03,373 --> 00:08:05,073
as any sort of marginalized folk online,

189
00:08:05,394 --> 00:08:07,335
we have to have our hackles up about this stuff

190
00:08:07,415 --> 00:08:09,896
because it's so often harmful and exploitative.

191
00:08:10,436 --> 00:08:11,857
So we're just trying to protect ourselves.

192
00:08:13,079 --> 00:08:15,220
And when something that comes out that's billed as queer,

193
00:08:15,801 --> 00:08:18,523
we put a lot of scrutiny on it because it can be really frustrating

194
00:08:18,543 --> 00:08:20,464
when you're desperate for media that represents you,

195
00:08:21,105 --> 00:08:21,826
and you never get any.

196
00:08:22,446 --> 00:08:24,608
And finally, something comes out that might speak to that,

197
00:08:24,808 --> 00:08:27,770
but actually, it's something you're not even remotely interested in,

198
00:08:28,431 --> 00:08:29,892
or, in our case, for a lot of folks,

199
00:08:30,012 --> 00:08:31,313
made it seem like they were the butt of the joke.

200
00:08:32,094 --> 00:08:34,976
And it's even worse when it seems like everyone is excited about it but you.

201
00:08:35,857 --> 00:08:37,738
And that can just feel like a slap in the face to players.

202
00:08:40,440 --> 00:08:40,540
And...

203
00:08:43,099 --> 00:08:46,761
Having spent years being an extremely logged on teen denizen of Tumblr,

204
00:08:47,161 --> 00:08:48,222
I've seen it from both sides.

205
00:08:48,902 --> 00:08:52,725
And the skepticism of the community is almost always valid and makes a lot of sense.

206
00:08:53,365 --> 00:08:55,547
But what I didn't realize until it happened to me

207
00:08:56,147 --> 00:08:59,549
was that when you have thousands of people piling on with thousands of different takes

208
00:08:59,629 --> 00:09:03,112
and accusations and speculation all at once, all the time,

209
00:09:03,432 --> 00:09:05,553
it's overwhelming as hell and it hurts.

210
00:09:06,614 --> 00:09:09,696
And most of all, it hurt because I felt like I was letting my community down.

211
00:09:10,276 --> 00:09:11,397
I didn't want to be that guy, ever.

212
00:09:12,923 --> 00:09:17,584
So I had dropped out of school temporarily and flown out to LA to help deliver this weird

213
00:09:17,604 --> 00:09:19,264
dad baby with the rest of the Dream Team.

214
00:09:20,445 --> 00:09:23,045
They're great, please thank them because they're wonderful people and very talented.

215
00:09:23,686 --> 00:09:23,926
Woo!

216
00:09:25,246 --> 00:09:25,606
They're good.

217
00:09:26,166 --> 00:09:26,866
Anyway, oh shit.

218
00:09:28,487 --> 00:09:30,487
So anyway, I flew out and it was hellish.

219
00:09:31,388 --> 00:09:33,088
This isn't a crunch talk, but we were wrecked.

220
00:09:33,688 --> 00:09:37,469
All-nighters, only going off of coffee and Soylent, the nicest people ever snapping at

221
00:09:37,489 --> 00:09:38,869
each other because everything was breaking.

222
00:09:39,390 --> 00:09:39,870
You know the drill.

223
00:09:41,142 --> 00:09:45,406
To compound this, at the last minute, we had to delay the game twice due to game-breaking

224
00:09:45,426 --> 00:09:45,726
bugs.

225
00:09:46,166 --> 00:09:47,788
You know, how crunch works.

226
00:09:48,768 --> 00:09:51,911
Cue even more yelling at us while we're all having some of the most stressful nights of

227
00:09:51,951 --> 00:09:52,311
our lives.

228
00:09:53,152 --> 00:09:57,015
So while we were getting nonstop tweets about how we didn't care about the fans, that this

229
00:09:57,055 --> 00:10:01,659
was evidence it was a cash grab, etc., we were all literally in tears trying to make

230
00:10:01,679 --> 00:10:05,842
this extremely hard decision to give ourselves more time, partially because our bodies were

231
00:10:05,862 --> 00:10:07,644
breaking down under the stress in long hours.

232
00:10:08,952 --> 00:10:13,383
Completely full disclosure, that month I had a period that lasted for 12 days because of

233
00:10:13,443 --> 00:10:14,666
how hard I was pushing my body.

234
00:10:15,468 --> 00:10:17,653
There was a point where I was throwing up from the stress.

235
00:10:18,174 --> 00:10:18,715
It was great!

236
00:10:20,757 --> 00:10:22,839
So that night after the second delay,

237
00:10:23,459 --> 00:10:25,981
Vern and I were both convinced that this whole thing was over,

238
00:10:26,242 --> 00:10:28,103
our careers were ruined, and we would

239
00:10:28,123 --> 00:10:29,084
get laughed off the internet.

240
00:10:29,684 --> 00:10:32,867
We were basically like, well, we had fun making it.

241
00:10:33,307 --> 00:10:35,049
That's kind of a year and a half down the drain, but hey,

242
00:10:35,569 --> 00:10:37,751
it'll be fine eventually, I guess.

243
00:10:39,292 --> 00:10:40,533
And the next morning, Dream Daddy

244
00:10:40,573 --> 00:10:42,255
was the top selling game on Steam globally.

245
00:10:42,995 --> 00:10:43,916
And people really loved it.

246
00:10:44,817 --> 00:10:46,098
So that is a thing that happened.

247
00:10:47,447 --> 00:10:50,791
Everything that came next was kind of a blur and a ridiculous whiplash from,

248
00:10:50,811 --> 00:10:54,154
well, this whole thing is over and I can never go on the internet again, to,

249
00:10:54,174 --> 00:10:58,659
oh, so my entire life just changed overnight and I can drop out of art school

250
00:10:58,699 --> 00:11:01,862
and fulfill a lifelong goal of moving to California now, question mark?

251
00:11:03,104 --> 00:11:05,245
Out of nowhere, we were suddenly absurdly successful.

252
00:11:05,906 --> 00:11:08,047
And yet, I didn't feel any differently

253
00:11:08,067 --> 00:11:09,087
than I had for the past month.

254
00:11:09,868 --> 00:11:11,729
I just felt kind of numb because of how surreal

255
00:11:11,789 --> 00:11:12,569
and sudden it all was.

256
00:11:13,189 --> 00:11:14,910
I flew home, I dropped out of school,

257
00:11:15,231 --> 00:11:17,292
I moved into a futon in my dad's spare room.

258
00:11:17,972 --> 00:11:20,233
My body was destroyed, I was exhausted.

259
00:11:20,673 --> 00:11:22,474
Crunching the internet stress fucked me up so bad

260
00:11:22,494 --> 00:11:24,876
that I was like sick and recovering for months.

261
00:11:25,676 --> 00:11:27,937
We continued to read everything about the game obsessively,

262
00:11:27,997 --> 00:11:30,939
which was again, never a good idea.

263
00:11:35,048 --> 00:11:38,951
And the funny thing about a lot of people loving a thing that you made is that not only

264
00:11:39,031 --> 00:11:44,076
is it a real dissociative trip mentally, but it becomes really easy to tune the positive

265
00:11:44,116 --> 00:11:49,721
stuff out and only focus on the negative because for some reason the negative stuff feels more

266
00:11:49,821 --> 00:11:50,521
true somehow.

267
00:11:51,122 --> 00:11:51,843
And there was a lot of it.

268
00:11:52,841 --> 00:11:56,364
So if your self-esteem is like a bowl that holds all of the wonderful positive things

269
00:11:56,404 --> 00:12:02,188
that people say, each bad tweet or email or message pokes a hole in the bowl until it's

270
00:12:02,208 --> 00:12:05,930
basically a strainer and it feels impossible to hold on to a shred of the good stuff.

271
00:12:06,691 --> 00:12:10,634
The imposter syndrome was really strong and as my career in the games industry started

272
00:12:10,654 --> 00:12:14,937
to form around the work that I did on Dads, the more I felt like I was still just a stupid

273
00:12:14,957 --> 00:12:16,898
art school dropout who had no idea what she was doing.

274
00:12:17,418 --> 00:12:18,799
Because I kind of was.

275
00:12:20,157 --> 00:12:25,282
And due to all the criticism, I was suddenly faced with the fact that even though we took

276
00:12:25,302 --> 00:12:28,305
all these steps to be as sensitive as possible, we fucked up.

277
00:12:29,026 --> 00:12:31,548
There are a lot of slip-ups we made that I still don't feel good about.

278
00:12:32,389 --> 00:12:36,072
And now looking back, I know that there's no such thing as positive representation and

279
00:12:36,092 --> 00:12:38,335
there never will be, which doesn't mean that we shouldn't try.

280
00:12:39,175 --> 00:12:43,539
But being forced to face that stuff over and over and over every day was a big learning

281
00:12:43,600 --> 00:12:44,400
experience for me.

282
00:12:45,261 --> 00:12:50,383
Now I'm even more committed to advocating for thoughtful representation and holding myself to a higher standard than I was before.

283
00:12:50,924 --> 00:12:54,506
But it still felt and feels just awful.

284
00:12:56,046 --> 00:13:00,869
Anyway, I had always thought that being successful would instantly make me happy and cure my depression,

285
00:13:00,949 --> 00:13:03,090
and when it didn't, it kind of tore me apart.

286
00:13:03,915 --> 00:13:04,876
Frankly, I was a wreck.

287
00:13:05,456 --> 00:13:07,136
I had to make my friends go through

288
00:13:07,196 --> 00:13:09,797
and clear my notifications and inboxes on everything.

289
00:13:10,357 --> 00:13:11,858
I isolated myself in real life.

290
00:13:12,358 --> 00:13:14,778
I ate junk food compulsively, stayed in bed all day,

291
00:13:15,219 --> 00:13:17,859
smoked too much weed, had to double my antidepressant dosage

292
00:13:17,879 --> 00:13:18,920
and get back on Xanax.

293
00:13:19,280 --> 00:13:23,281
And yeah, we had done it, and I felt like a failure.

294
00:13:25,188 --> 00:13:27,690
When I was in art school, I had this recurring nightmare

295
00:13:27,750 --> 00:13:30,451
where I'd be in a critique, but instead of my art,

296
00:13:31,092 --> 00:13:32,292
I'd be the one being critiqued.

297
00:13:32,712 --> 00:13:34,593
And everyone in the class would tear

298
00:13:34,633 --> 00:13:37,075
into all my personal flaws, but then when I left class,

299
00:13:37,635 --> 00:13:38,836
they would follow me around campus

300
00:13:38,896 --> 00:13:41,477
and then huddle around my bed at night still critiquing.

301
00:13:42,638 --> 00:13:45,279
And that's how being online felt for a really long time.

302
00:13:46,160 --> 00:13:48,521
Even my subconscious is extremely on the nose.

303
00:13:50,811 --> 00:13:54,796
So the good news is that even though it took a lot of time of me being completely miserable,

304
00:13:55,316 --> 00:13:58,780
I'm in a lot better place mentally than I was a few years ago, and I'm a lot stronger

305
00:13:58,820 --> 00:13:59,241
for it too.

306
00:14:00,342 --> 00:14:04,286
I still struggle with my mental health and the imposter syndrome all the time, but that's

307
00:14:04,326 --> 00:14:05,588
just kind of how my brain is.

308
00:14:07,130 --> 00:14:10,892
Through a lot of intensive therapy, getting heavily medicated, and a ton of self-help

309
00:14:10,932 --> 00:14:15,315
and psychology textbooks I bought on Amazon Prime, I found a lot better coping mechanisms

310
00:14:15,335 --> 00:14:16,195
to help me get through it.

311
00:14:17,036 --> 00:14:20,318
And at the end of this talk, there'll be a page with a link to a breakdown of all those

312
00:14:20,358 --> 00:14:21,898
practical self-care tips I learned.

313
00:14:22,839 --> 00:14:26,141
But while I'm up here in person, I'd rather talk about the biggest thing that helped me

314
00:14:26,181 --> 00:14:26,741
get through this.

315
00:14:27,201 --> 00:14:32,224
And because I love to overly intellectualize my feelings, that was trying to understand

316
00:14:32,704 --> 00:14:34,025
why the internet works like this.

317
00:14:36,599 --> 00:14:38,640
As we struggled with this, we discovered that actually,

318
00:14:38,920 --> 00:14:42,241
this experience is extremely common among people

319
00:14:42,281 --> 00:14:43,761
who make popular pieces of media.

320
00:14:44,781 --> 00:14:46,602
We were lucky enough to be able to talk to people

321
00:14:46,642 --> 00:14:48,242
who went through it and came out the other side

322
00:14:48,282 --> 00:14:50,643
in one piece, and that was ridiculously comforting.

323
00:14:52,283 --> 00:14:54,384
But we don't talk about this stuff in public spaces

324
00:14:54,464 --> 00:14:56,925
because it's basically admitting that all of the angry

325
00:14:57,025 --> 00:14:59,726
emails and tweets worked, that you let it get to you.

326
00:15:00,266 --> 00:15:01,926
You're successful, who cares?

327
00:15:02,086 --> 00:15:03,147
It's what you signed up for.

328
00:15:03,587 --> 00:15:05,327
It's just the internet, right?

329
00:15:06,796 --> 00:15:09,158
And the idea of being vulnerable and real online

330
00:15:09,238 --> 00:15:10,759
after going through that kind of experience

331
00:15:10,919 --> 00:15:12,420
is kind of terrifying.

332
00:15:13,321 --> 00:15:14,982
It does make you want to log off entirely

333
00:15:15,022 --> 00:15:16,583
just so you don't have to deal with it anymore.

334
00:15:17,483 --> 00:15:19,665
Honestly, it's pretty scary talking about it up here today.

335
00:15:21,326 --> 00:15:23,888
But my intent isn't to throw some sob story at you

336
00:15:23,908 --> 00:15:26,190
to get pity or even cast aspersions

337
00:15:26,250 --> 00:15:27,611
on people who didn't like Dream Daddy

338
00:15:27,631 --> 00:15:30,553
because it is completely allowed and valid actually.

339
00:15:31,633 --> 00:15:34,115
But I tell you this because the experience forced me

340
00:15:34,155 --> 00:15:36,157
to reexamine the way that I engage with the internet.

341
00:15:40,836 --> 00:15:42,257
I love to feel like I'm drinking half and half.

342
00:15:44,899 --> 00:15:48,942
Whenever I tell this sordid tale at conventions, I always hear the same thing, and it breaks

343
00:15:48,982 --> 00:15:50,243
my heart more and more every time.

344
00:15:51,604 --> 00:15:55,727
When I'm talking to young game designers, I always hear that, based on the public reaction

345
00:15:55,747 --> 00:16:00,031
that creators get when they try to put out work that attempts to tackle any sort of serious,

346
00:16:00,111 --> 00:16:04,374
complex issue, it makes them afraid to even try to put their work out there.

347
00:16:05,234 --> 00:16:06,876
And that's the worst possible outcome.

348
00:16:07,968 --> 00:16:12,109
Because if the ultimate goal of discourse and brigading creators and calling them out

349
00:16:12,149 --> 00:16:16,890
for their fiction is to make representation better, more diverse, and more respectful,

350
00:16:17,450 --> 00:16:18,290
then we've failed.

351
00:16:19,531 --> 00:16:24,512
If we have kids who are so afraid of being dogpiled by not only ignorant idiots, but

352
00:16:24,612 --> 00:16:28,773
also their own communities, then we're essentially bullying them into virtual non-existence,

353
00:16:29,173 --> 00:16:31,053
and then we're losing those stories entirely.

354
00:16:32,366 --> 00:16:34,587
And to be clear, I'm not saying that anyone

355
00:16:34,627 --> 00:16:37,048
is immune to criticism or that we should eliminate discourse.

356
00:16:37,468 --> 00:16:38,929
Having public critical discussions

357
00:16:38,989 --> 00:16:41,310
of work that analyzes the ways in which it's successful

358
00:16:41,470 --> 00:16:44,072
and ways in which it's harmful is literally the only way

359
00:16:44,112 --> 00:16:44,892
we can move forward.

360
00:16:45,753 --> 00:16:48,814
What I am saying is that the way we have these discussions

361
00:16:48,874 --> 00:16:49,174
matter.

362
00:16:51,015 --> 00:16:53,897
Flattening complex issues into the hottest take possible

363
00:16:54,697 --> 00:16:55,537
is not productive.

364
00:16:56,638 --> 00:16:59,259
Twitter should be used as a tool to facilitate discussion,

365
00:17:00,240 --> 00:17:01,120
not to shut it down.

366
00:17:02,852 --> 00:17:05,293
And like any tool, it can be used for good and bad.

367
00:17:05,733 --> 00:17:07,174
You can use a hammer to build a house,

368
00:17:07,314 --> 00:17:10,136
but you can also use it to smash someone's kneecaps in,

369
00:17:10,897 --> 00:17:11,477
metaphorically.

370
00:17:13,138 --> 00:17:14,319
Part of learning how to do better

371
00:17:14,479 --> 00:17:16,480
is by admitting that you don't know what you're doing.

372
00:17:17,181 --> 00:17:19,342
Part of maturing is having space to fail

373
00:17:19,402 --> 00:17:20,423
without getting canceled.

374
00:17:21,263 --> 00:17:23,465
And part of learning about yourself and about others

375
00:17:23,565 --> 00:17:26,046
is to explore the shades of gray between black and white,

376
00:17:26,627 --> 00:17:27,647
and by wading into the things

377
00:17:27,688 --> 00:17:29,869
that you don't know you don't know together.

378
00:17:31,138 --> 00:17:33,001
And there's a lot of value in work that fails.

379
00:17:33,741 --> 00:17:35,263
It's a collective learning experience

380
00:17:35,303 --> 00:17:36,304
rather than a personal one.

381
00:17:37,465 --> 00:17:40,028
But we shouldn't be robbing ourselves of opportunities

382
00:17:40,068 --> 00:17:42,511
to get better just because we want to be capital R right.

383
00:17:43,752 --> 00:17:45,755
And unfortunately, marginalized creators

384
00:17:45,815 --> 00:17:47,557
making work about their own experience

385
00:17:47,637 --> 00:17:50,700
that is messy or dark or imperfect

386
00:17:50,840 --> 00:17:52,222
are disproportionately targeted.

387
00:17:53,375 --> 00:17:55,297
not only by the ignorant shitheads we'd expect,

388
00:17:55,677 --> 00:17:57,098
but also by their own communities.

389
00:17:57,739 --> 00:17:59,981
And to be extremely clear, I do not mean this is like a,

390
00:18:00,241 --> 00:18:02,843
blah, both sides are just as bad thing at all,

391
00:18:03,083 --> 00:18:05,145
because that's a stupid and dangerous rhetoric,

392
00:18:05,225 --> 00:18:06,786
and that is not what I'm trying to say.

393
00:18:07,967 --> 00:18:11,050
But we have a responsibility to hold space for that

394
00:18:11,150 --> 00:18:12,651
and protect the most vulnerable members

395
00:18:12,691 --> 00:18:13,692
of our network online,

396
00:18:14,132 --> 00:18:16,975
just like we need to do in real life and our fiction.

397
00:18:17,861 --> 00:18:20,222
And if we're ripping people to shreds over not being perfect

398
00:18:20,362 --> 00:18:23,062
and not making perfect work that perfectly represents everyone,

399
00:18:23,302 --> 00:18:24,943
we're just eating our own tails here.

400
00:18:26,783 --> 00:18:29,704
This is especially discouraging because IRL queer spaces

401
00:18:29,764 --> 00:18:31,925
are being eliminated en masse through a combination

402
00:18:31,965 --> 00:18:34,345
of gentrification, the proliferation of dating apps,

403
00:18:34,386 --> 00:18:36,366
and the fact that young queer people have more access

404
00:18:36,386 --> 00:18:37,186
to each other online.

405
00:18:38,067 --> 00:18:40,047
Honestly, this is a whole talk in itself, so I will stop.

406
00:18:40,367 --> 00:18:43,528
But there is no replacement for physically surrounding yourself

407
00:18:43,648 --> 00:18:44,448
with people like you.

408
00:18:45,048 --> 00:18:46,749
There is safety and strength in that.

409
00:18:47,561 --> 00:18:50,463
There's no replacement for activism and organizing in person.

410
00:18:51,104 --> 00:18:53,926
And there's also no replacement for having these important discussions

411
00:18:53,966 --> 00:18:56,388
about complex issues like queerness in person.

412
00:18:56,948 --> 00:18:59,730
And especially in this goddamn political climate,

413
00:19:00,071 --> 00:19:02,833
the fact that we're replacing the warmth of IRL queer spaces

414
00:19:02,893 --> 00:19:06,616
with fighting each other to the death online over fictional characters

415
00:19:07,076 --> 00:19:08,217
makes me want to cry.

416
00:19:10,238 --> 00:19:12,100
And aside from existing unconscious bias,

417
00:19:12,200 --> 00:19:15,382
I think a big part of the reason this happens is because of the sheer access.

418
00:19:16,434 --> 00:19:18,556
Smaller creators, especially indie creators,

419
00:19:18,676 --> 00:19:20,438
who rely on the attention economy

420
00:19:20,498 --> 00:19:22,000
and by branding themselves online

421
00:19:22,080 --> 00:19:23,281
are particularly vulnerable.

422
00:19:24,462 --> 00:19:26,324
There's a higher likelihood of a tangible result

423
00:19:26,364 --> 00:19:29,347
of adding them, say, than there is of repeatedly adding

424
00:19:29,387 --> 00:19:31,089
Marvel or any other big celebrity

425
00:19:31,189 --> 00:19:32,530
who are perceived as inaccessible.

426
00:19:33,511 --> 00:19:34,632
And by getting someone fired,

427
00:19:34,772 --> 00:19:35,894
getting their project canceled,

428
00:19:36,114 --> 00:19:37,635
or just getting them to delete their account,

429
00:19:37,956 --> 00:19:40,358
that's a tangible outcome that rewards that behavior.

430
00:19:41,335 --> 00:19:44,836
And we've seen over and over how this approach has been utilized in a positive way.

431
00:19:44,856 --> 00:19:46,557
I mean, you can just look at the Me Too movement.

432
00:19:47,577 --> 00:19:52,099
But we can't immediately go from a nuanced critique of a piece of media to jumping to

433
00:19:52,159 --> 00:19:56,680
conclusions about its creator in the same way we oust predators because it's then it's

434
00:19:56,720 --> 00:20:00,141
not actually about discussing media or even keeping the community safe anymore.

435
00:20:00,982 --> 00:20:04,543
It's about the exchange of social capital, but we'll get to that in a second.

436
00:20:05,823 --> 00:20:06,843
So this sucks.

437
00:20:08,487 --> 00:20:10,389
You ever hear of the crab bucket mentality?

438
00:20:11,350 --> 00:20:13,271
It's the idea that when crabs are trapped in a bucket,

439
00:20:13,531 --> 00:20:14,933
any of them could potentially escape.

440
00:20:15,853 --> 00:20:17,194
But instead what happens is the ones

441
00:20:17,234 --> 00:20:18,415
that get close to escaping

442
00:20:18,836 --> 00:20:20,257
get pulled back down by the other crabs.

443
00:20:20,837 --> 00:20:22,539
It's very much like, if I can't have it,

444
00:20:22,579 --> 00:20:23,199
then neither can you.

445
00:20:24,180 --> 00:20:25,922
And that's exactly what's happening on socials,

446
00:20:26,042 --> 00:20:26,982
especially Twitter.

447
00:20:27,723 --> 00:20:29,585
And while this is pretty basic human behavior,

448
00:20:29,745 --> 00:20:31,907
the affordances of the internet are exacerbating it.

449
00:20:32,227 --> 00:20:32,527
Namely.

450
00:20:34,036 --> 00:20:37,940
context collapse, temporal collapse, parasocial relationships,

451
00:20:38,360 --> 00:20:40,202
and the gamified exchange of social capital.

452
00:20:42,104 --> 00:20:44,707
And learning about these concepts and how they're in play on the internet

453
00:20:44,887 --> 00:20:46,349
helped me find a lot of peace with this stuff.

454
00:20:46,709 --> 00:20:49,352
As I said, over-intellectualizing feelings, it's a thing.

455
00:20:50,073 --> 00:20:51,374
So, let's talk about it.

456
00:20:53,676 --> 00:20:56,359
The way we present ourselves changes based on who we're with, right?

457
00:20:57,482 --> 00:20:59,563
You could say that our identities are contextual.

458
00:21:00,223 --> 00:21:01,383
The way you talk to your parents

459
00:21:01,543 --> 00:21:03,104
is different from the way you talk to your friends,

460
00:21:03,324 --> 00:21:05,505
romantic partners, your boss, colleagues,

461
00:21:05,565 --> 00:21:06,606
or strangers on the street.

462
00:21:07,386 --> 00:21:09,147
You can't have a personality in a vacuum.

463
00:21:09,987 --> 00:21:11,708
It's not that we fundamentally change ourselves

464
00:21:11,728 --> 00:21:13,129
when we interact with different people,

465
00:21:13,689 --> 00:21:15,630
but that we display different facets of ourselves

466
00:21:15,690 --> 00:21:18,051
in different situations because it's based on knowledge

467
00:21:18,071 --> 00:21:19,391
of who we're presenting it to.

468
00:21:20,628 --> 00:21:22,410
This is why it's so annoying when people comment

469
00:21:22,430 --> 00:21:24,512
on how social media is inherently performative,

470
00:21:24,553 --> 00:21:25,474
like that's a bad thing.

471
00:21:26,014 --> 00:21:27,796
Existing itself is performative.

472
00:21:28,357 --> 00:21:29,178
That's not a problem.

473
00:21:29,378 --> 00:21:29,919
That's awesome.

474
00:21:30,660 --> 00:21:32,081
But what is a problem, though,

475
00:21:32,302 --> 00:21:35,165
is that self-performance online can't be regulated

476
00:21:35,205 --> 00:21:36,266
in any meaningful way

477
00:21:36,366 --> 00:21:39,130
because you don't know who your audience is.

478
00:21:40,209 --> 00:21:44,832
At any given time, you have the concept of your followers, but this is an imagined audience,

479
00:21:45,172 --> 00:21:49,034
and you have no way of knowing how much of that imagined audience overlaps with the people

480
00:21:49,074 --> 00:21:49,955
who actually see it.

481
00:21:50,715 --> 00:21:54,758
Thus, you have virtually no control over how you're presenting yourself or being perceived.

482
00:21:55,318 --> 00:21:57,559
Your identity becomes something that others build for you.

483
00:21:58,960 --> 00:22:00,601
This is what context collapse means.

484
00:22:01,347 --> 00:22:04,030
We have never had this level of immediate global communication

485
00:22:04,070 --> 00:22:05,371
with each other, ever.

486
00:22:05,972 --> 00:22:07,633
Thus, we have no rules for navigating

487
00:22:07,673 --> 00:22:09,635
the levels of multifaceted self-performance

488
00:22:09,655 --> 00:22:11,837
the platform requires, no way of understanding

489
00:22:11,857 --> 00:22:14,020
the cultural nuance of the random people we interact with,

490
00:22:14,480 --> 00:22:16,842
no facial or body cues we can use to inflect tone.

491
00:22:17,483 --> 00:22:20,767
We have people of all ages, from children to the elderly, from disparate backgrounds,

492
00:22:20,787 --> 00:22:23,911
with different levels of life experience and education, all tossed in together on a few

493
00:22:23,931 --> 00:22:27,715
bespoke platforms that have no design unifying purpose other than vague terms like to share

494
00:22:27,855 --> 00:22:28,516
and communicate.

495
00:22:29,117 --> 00:22:31,119
I mean, and also to make money off of you fighting.

496
00:22:31,700 --> 00:22:32,621
It's absurd.

497
00:22:33,061 --> 00:22:36,806
It's amazing that we can get anyone to agree on anything with this, this many cultural

498
00:22:36,846 --> 00:22:37,807
and social balls in the air.

499
00:22:40,109 --> 00:22:44,152
